TextBlock.TextLine: In Antwerpen 6 Janu 1681
Brussel Hendrick De smet
Mons. in antwoort vanden ul van 4 deser wenck ul de terse
drogette ofte ratinne daer ul van had gesprock als Leelt tot rssel was
sijn doort gaet weder & herte yeganck, in England op gehouden als leeft
bij ul was had advis als dat schip al was vertrocken, sedort dat selve
te ruyge heeft moetkeeren, soo dan in geralle voor nu met den west
wint nieten is gearriveed tot ostend voor mij seer scadelijck sal sijn
heb daer ordre geven om die met wagens terrewaert t senden soo haet
die trreveren, waer van gets vernemen sulel anstonts laete wetey
Brussel Bernaerd vander klootter
In Antwerpen 6 Januarj 1681
Mons. in antwoort vande ul wensch & de perse paye oft Engelsch
Ratiene gelijck sij sijn, sijn tot mijn leet wesen noch niet tots stend
gearriveert, ende als leett tot brussel was hadaevies datse van England
vertrocken waren sedert p quatwedert srugge geloopen soo die arrin
sullen p wagen gesonden als wanneer aen ul in tijts sal advisen
ende soo dan niet te laet is kan ul sijn ordre senden, de witte frisor
kan voor 11 t niet geven het soude ten alder minste 11½ p moeten
wesen gelijck de kosten soo d'iersch bay noch dese weke komen sal
ul een provve senden -
Brussel wen
bonnecoloj
In Antwerpen 6 Janu 1681
op 3 deser hebbe aen ul gescreven daer aen mij referre heden de
2 lapen canten ontf. soo haest de andere gereetsijn gelieft mij de litte
te senden adviseert mij wat met de bree kanten hebbondemonen
soo eenigh assoot van tryall werck boven voorskon kekomen
soo vvan watten als mangsat begeerne noch wel 5 a 3oll dat
soude alleen wesen waert saken ul iets ter kant a umeest
trayll werck vant geene passeert scrijft advies sal in d'eijnde van dese
maent met godts gratie tot brussel wesen
Leuven Joan van Obstal
In Antwerpen 6 Janu 81
mio
Mons. in antwoort vanden ul van P. Deser wenschen de hondert
Guldens p: Bodegelens gebroght sijn wel geanoteert als mede het
wisselbriefken van £25: tot laste van de paters inswnten middeltit
soo iets voor valt waer in ul kandienen gelieft liberljck te commandeer
In Antwerpen 6 Januar1681
Leuven guill Le febvre
Mons. moet ul andermael aen maenen om mijne Restant te vol doen also
buijten alle mede gaet ick en kan mijne principalle daer mede geen sins
satisfactie geven oversulx laet mij ul versoeck nu niet lanser te deliere
de rest te voldoen boven dien versoeck gelieft te betaelen aen mijn broeder
beeraerd: melijn Aug o 50: & de lest p bode mij te senden waer op mij verlatende
In Antwerp 7 Janurj 1681
Lille Richd. Southell
th
S. in answer to yd of 5 curitt I shall perused the acctt of sale for us in
comp. & note all things accordingly: in our acctt crits you pl case to
make mee debter &ort107: 3:10 for yd ½ in the proceed o 121 of
hose & 28 p stuffs, besides £10 for yd ½ in 10 hatts as also the proceed
of the bales of kersyes the times is to short to send you the perticulas
whoever p next you may exspect itt whilst please to send my ser
n acctt curitt thought not ballanced to see if I have no mistakes inne
so I shall exspect that without any faile. I observe yd complaints &
straights by reason of H.C. I must tell you, that I have been of late
pu blickley blamed for dealing with him nay those that en vre mee
dare op entley say that either he or I can not hold itt long & this steal
my creditt, where ford I have been obliged to take in 2 bills each of £150:
which I had redrawne or him & remitt them my self, for feare that
they might have fallen in to handes of others that are my pertie &
not withstanding H.C. hath drawne about £400: so I am now
resolved to cleare all & lett him alsone he hath foind some boddy
to sul TH. which doubt less will blame mee for itt, nay if he thinkes
of no revange, I am sorrj for yd disapointnent I have look about thise
day to remitt you, butt coald nott finde & bill & the indorser in blanco:
I must tell you that itt should be agreat preindice to mee to accept such
a bill butt if you can not pray gett some boddy Elce to draw directly
& ill accept £100: a £150 att 2 uso or one acoording you finde the connenient
because for you to proffer my accepted bill on theer would certainly
cause an in formation affer mee a great prcubation tomy disorett
yett w henyeu draw direitely yo bill shall finde du honoir, I hope
then tH Chath set provssion or at least RW will assien
yeu in such eneravaae, hun if I had knownbefore
could have precent ad itt
In Antwerp 7 January 1681
Cadix John Gardner &comp
S. this by order of mr. Joseph Rokely of London forcorart to the inclosed bills first
& second with cettifilates & protest att the charge of Daniel cothen & wijbers, as
you will finde larger peruseing the same, I not haveing beenable to groceire any
valew here please to follow the order of said mr. Rokely & in what occasion
I can serve you here freely command him that is
In Antwerp 7 January 1681
London Joseph Robely
Sr sence I have recd. yd of 29 gb last, have not been contented with what endeavours
I had don nyd behalfe concerning the bill of John de commek, butt caused the
papers (which you sent me to be examined againe in amanner of 2
heferrence & they discharged John de coninck, because the first, or second bill
was not duely protested. so that I could do no good ur on him whereffore have
this day sent for spane, according to yd order to m. John gardner & comp
the first & second bill with the 2 protests & the other certificates I never had
or Fomd amonghst George shaw: papers, neither any other matter materials
I could wish to meet on other opporturitie to do you a better & more aggrealle
service whilst & wish you an happy & prosperons new year & remaine
In Antwarp 7 Jauu 1681
London Henry Maynard
th
S my last to you was on the 4 curitt when remitted you £200: on John Lambe
N.
£100p on will Iurret for my acctt. when the £150: you accepted for mee
shall be due, shall be discharged here, where with mj curitt shall ballance very
neare now for yd acctt exspect order to send more gold or byen by my last somitted
forwant of time the inclosed pattarnes & instructions according to which
l case to governe yd self & thought I want no spanish cloathes yett itt
is in hopes, that you shall finde pennj worths & good cullours to be here
in lent, wee heare no nows of Ben. Clarck I hope he heth not suffered by
the late stormes: I could wish to know wherepis & so remaine
anclosed the accepted bill of John vale
